text: Well, thanks for inviting me, Corey. It would be very interesting to talk about the two of you. So I was a physics PhD at many cons. But after I got my PhD from Cornell, I did nothing about physics. I immediately pursued my passion, which was and is machine learning. So I got to work for a group at the IBM T.J. Watson Research Center called Human Language Technologies Group. Now, that group was a bit in the news lately because of a biography on Jim Simons, the founder of Renaissance Technologies. It turns out that until recently, the two co-CEOs of Rantech were managers in my group. I did not meet them. I missed them by one year. They already went to Rantech when I joined. But many of the current portfolio managers of Rantech were my colleagues in that group as well. So I enjoyed three good years working with this high-tech group. I was a very interesting team at IBM before I moved on to join Morgan Stanley Data Mining and AI Group, which is a fairly new group within the firm that provides machine learning consulting to various business units. And after that, I embarked on a number of trading careers, working with different pop trading desks at different banks and hedge funds, until 2006 when I started to trade for myself and then later on managing money for clients and writing for myself.
